1 (G) a private landowner who does not have a conservation easement
2 on the land and currently provides public access, appointed by the Speaker of
3 the House;
4 (H) a representative who has expertise in trail planning, design,
5 building, and maintenance, appointed by the Committee on Committees; and
6 (I) a representative of the Vermont League of Cities and Towns,
7 appointed by the Governor.
8 (2) The Study Committee may invite other entities to participate in the
9 conduct of the study as non-voting participants.
10 (c) Powers and duties. The Recreational Trails Compensation Study
11 Committee shall:
12 (1) review how private property currently is made available for use by
13 public recreational trails;
14 (2) summarize the costs and liabilities that private property owners incur
15 when private property is used by public recreational trails;
16 (3) assess available economic data and other relevant available data or
17 analysis and conduct further necessary economic analysis to determine the
18 value that recreational trail access provides to the State and to local economies;
19 (4) investigate whether and how private property owners in other
20 jurisdictions are compensated for allowing use of property for public
21 recreational trails or other public outdoor recreation;
