1 (5) recommend to the General Assembly whether real property owners
2 who allow use of their property for public recreational trails should receive
3 compensation or other benefit and, if so, the source of the compensation or
4 other benefit;
5 (6) how to ensure trail siting, design, construction, and management
6 meet minimum standards; and
7 (7) how to ensure that new trail development is established based on the
8 merit of the opportunity being created in comparison to any incentive provided
9 to a private landowner.
10 (d) Assistance. The Recreational Trails Compensation Study Committee
11 shall have the administrative, technical, and legal assistance of the Department
12 of Forests, Parks and Recreation.
13 (e) Report. On or before December 15, 2026, the Recreational Trails
14 Compensation Study Committee shall submit a written report to the General
15 Assembly with its findings and any recommendations for legislative action.
16 (f) Meetings.
17 (1) The Commissioner of Forests, Parks and Recreation or designee
18 shall call the first meeting of the Recreational Trails Compensation Study
19 Committee to occur on or before September 15, 2025.
20 (2) The Commissioner of Forests, Parks and Recreation or designee
21 shall be the chair of the Study Committee.
